<H3><A NAME="research">Research:</A></H3>
I work in quantum computing as well as knowledge representation and
logic programming.
<P>
<b>Quantum computing:</b> My work is primarily in quantum networking and
distributed quantum computing, and efficient simulation of quantum
computation. Current projects include:
<UL>
  <LI><em>Entanglement distibution in quantum neworks</em> (joint with
  Prof. Himanshu Gupta): Algorithms and protocols for efficiently
  distributing entangled states (Bell pairs, GHZ states, Graph states)
  across nodes of a quantum network.
  <LI><em>Distributed quantum computing</em> (joint with Prof. Himanshu
  Gupta): Resource-Efficient <i>distributed</i> evaluation of a quantum
  circuit/program over a network of quantum processors.
  <LI><em>Efficient simulation of quantum programs</em> (joint with
  Profs. Dmitri Kharzeev/SBU Physics and Kazuki Ikeda/UMass-Boston) to evaluate ground
  and excited states of quantum systems on classical high-performance
  computers.
</UL>
<P>
<b>Logic programming and knowledge representation:</b> I work on
representing and reasoning over incomplete and noisy data. Towards
this my work focuses on combining statistical and logical
knowledge: ways to represent such knowledge, learn, and perform inference over
such knowledge. Current projects include:
<UL>
  <LI><em>Robotic manipulation in human environments</em> (joint with
  Profs. Nilanjan Chakraborty/SBU Mech. Engg. and IV Ramakrishnan),
  where the robot needs to perform activities reliably and
  autonomously in the presence of sensor noise, incomplete
  understanding of the environment, and actuation errors. The current
  application is to build assistive robots for people with locomotor
  difficulties.
</UL>
<P>
See <A HREF="research.html">here</A> for more details on my current
and past research; and <A HREF="#news">here</A> for recent research news.
